#: ../../../tutorial.rst:4
msgid "Tutorial"
msgstr "教學"

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:7
msgid "Why fish?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:9
msgid ""
"Fish is a fully-equipped command line shell (like bash or zsh) that is smart "
"and user-friendly. Fish supports powerful features like syntax highlighting, "
"autosuggestions, and tab completions that just work, with nothing to learn "
"or configure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:11
msgid ""
"If you want to make your command line more productive, more useful, and more "
"fun, without learning a bunch of arcane syntax and configuration options, "
"then fish might be just what you're looking for!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:15
msgid "Getting started"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:17
msgid ""
"Once installed, just type in ``fish`` into your current shell to try it out!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:19
msgid ""
"You will be greeted by the standard fish prompt, which means you are all set "
"up and can start using fish::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:22
msgid ""
"> fish\n"
"Welcome to fish, the friendly interactive shell\n"
"Type help for instructions on how to use fish\n"
"you@hostname ~>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:28
msgid ""
"This prompt that you see above is the fish default prompt: it shows your "
"username, hostname, and working directory. You can customize it, see :ref:"
"`how to change your prompt <prompt>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:30
msgid "From now on, we'll pretend your prompt is just a ``>`` to save space."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:34
msgid "Learning fish"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:36
msgid ""
"This tutorial assumes a basic understanding of command line shells and Unix "
"commands, and that you have a working copy of fish."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:38
msgid ""
"If you have a strong understanding of other shells, and want to know what "
"fish does differently, search for the magic phrase *unlike other shells*, "
"which is used to call out important differences."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:40
msgid ""
"Or, if you want a quick overview over the differences to other shells like "
"Bash, see :doc:`Fish For Bash Users <fish_for_bash_users>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:42
msgid ""
"For the full, detailed description of how to use fish interactively, see :"
"doc:`Interactive Use <interactive>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:44
msgid ""
"For a comprehensive description of fish's scripting language, see :doc:`The "
"Fish Language <language>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:47
msgid "Running Commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:49
msgid ""
"Fish runs commands like other shells: you type a command, followed by its "
"arguments. Spaces are separators::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:51
msgid ""
"> echo hello world\n"
"hello world"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:55
msgid ""
"This runs the command ``echo`` with the arguments ``hello`` and ``world``. "
"In this case that's the same as one argument ``hello world``, but in many "
"cases it's not. If you need to pass an argument that includes a space, you "
"can :ref:`escape <escapes>` with a backslash, or :ref:`quote <quotes>` it "
"using single or double quotes::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:57
msgid ""
"> mkdir My\\ Files\n"
"# Makes a directory called \"My Files\", with a space in the name\n"
"> cp ~/Some\\ File 'My Files'\n"
"# Copies a file called \"Some File\" in the home directory to \"My Files\"\n"
"> ls \"My Files\"\n"
"Some File"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:66
msgid "Getting Help"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:68
msgid ""
"Run ``help`` to open fish's help in a web browser, and ``man`` with the page "
"(like ``fish-language``) to open it in a man page. You can also ask for help "
"with a specific command, for example, ``help set`` to open in a web browser, "
"or ``man set`` to see it in the terminal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:72
msgid ""
"> man set\n"
"set - handle shell variables\n"
"  Synopsis..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:76
msgid "To open this section, use ``help getting-help``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:78
msgid ""
"This only works for fish's own documentation for itself and its built-in "
"commands (the \"builtins\"). For any other commands on your system, they "
"should provide their own documentation, often in the man system. For example "
"``man ls`` should tell you about your computer's ``ls`` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:81
msgid "Syntax Highlighting"
msgstr "語法標明"

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:90
msgid ""
"You'll quickly notice that fish performs syntax highlighting as you type. "
"Invalid commands are colored red by default:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:95
msgid ":prompt:`>` :red:`/bin/mkd`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:97
msgid ""
"A command may be invalid because it does not exist, or refers to a file that "
"you cannot execute. When the command becomes valid, it is shown in a "
"different color::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:99
msgid "> /bin/mkdir"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:102
msgid "Valid file paths are underlined as you type them:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:107
msgid ":prompt:`>` :command:`cat` :param-valid-path:`~/somefi`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:110
msgid ""
"This tells you that there exists a file that starts with ``somefi``, which "
"is useful feedback as you type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:112
msgid ""
"These colors, and many more, can be changed by running ``fish_config``, or "
"by modifying :ref:`color variables <variables-color>` directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:114
msgid "For example, if you want to disable (almost) all coloring::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:116
msgid "fish_config theme choose none"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:118
msgid "This picks the \"none\" theme. To see all themes::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:120
msgid "fish_config theme show"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:122
msgid ""
"Just running ``fish_config`` will open up a browser interface that allows "
"you to pick from the available themes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:125
msgid "Autosuggestions"
msgstr "自動建議"

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:127
msgid ""
"As you type fish will suggest commands to the right of the cursor, in gray. "
"For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:132
msgid ":prompt:`>` :red:`/bin/h`:gray:`ostname`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:135
msgid "It knows about paths and options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:140
msgid ":prompt:`>` :command:`grep` :param:`--i`:gray:`gnore-case`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:143
msgid ""
"And history too. Type a command once, and you can re-summon it by just "
"typing a few letters:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:148
msgid ""
":prompt:`>` :red:`r`:gray:`sync -avze ssh . myname@somelonghost.com:/some/"
"long/path/doo/dee/doo/dee/doo`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:151
msgid ""
"To accept the autosuggestion, hit :kbd:`right` (``→``) or :kbd:`ctrl-f`. To "
"accept a single word of the autosuggestion, :kbd:`alt-right` (``→``). If the "
"autosuggestion is not what you want, just ignore it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:153
msgid ""
"If you don't like autosuggestions, you can disable them by setting "
"``$fish_autosuggestion_enabled`` to 0::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:155
msgid "set -g fish_autosuggestion_enabled 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:158
msgid "Tab Completions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:160
msgid "A rich set of tab completions work \"out of the box\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:162
msgid ""
"Press :kbd:`tab` and fish will attempt to complete the command, argument, or "
"path:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:167
msgid ":prompt:`>` :red:`/pri`:kbd:`tab` => :command:`/private/`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:170
msgid "If there's more than one possibility, it will list them:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:175
msgid ""
":prompt:`>` :red:`~/stuff/s`:kbd:`tab`\n"
"~/stuff/script.sh  :gray:`(command)`  ~/stuff/sources/  :gray:`(directory)`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:179
msgid ""
"Hit tab again to cycle through the possibilities. The part in parentheses "
"there (that \"command\" and \"directory\") is the completion description. "
"It's just a short hint to explain what kind of argument it is."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:181
msgid "fish can also complete many commands, like git branches:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:186
msgid ""
":prompt:`>` :command:`git` :param:`merge pr`:kbd:`tab` => :command:`git` :"
"param:`merge prompt_designer`\n"
":prompt:`>` :command:`git` :param:`checkout b`:kbd:`tab`\n"
"builtin_list_io_merge :gray:`(Branch)`  builtin_set_color :gray:`(Branch)` "
"busted_events :gray:`(Tag)`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:190
msgid "Try hitting tab and see what fish can do!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:193
msgid "Variables"
msgstr "變數"

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:195
msgid ""
"Like other shells, a dollar sign followed by a variable name is replaced "
"with the value of that variable::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:197
msgid ""
"> echo My home directory is $HOME\n"
"My home directory is /home/tutorial"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:200
msgid ""
"This is known as variable substitution, and it also happens in double "
"quotes, but not single quotes::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:202
msgid ""
"> echo \"My current directory is $PWD\"\n"
"My current directory is /home/tutorial\n"
"> echo 'My current directory is $PWD'\n"
"My current directory is $PWD"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:207
msgid ""
"Unlike other shells, fish has an ordinary command to set variables: ``set``, "
"which takes a variable name, and then its value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:211
msgid ""
"> set name 'Mister Noodle'\n"
"> echo $name\n"
"Mister Noodle"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:216
msgid ""
"(Notice the quotes: without them, ``Mister`` and ``Noodle`` would have been "
"separate arguments, and ``$name`` would have been made into a list of two "
"elements.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:218
msgid ""
"Unlike other shells, variables are not further split after substitution::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:220
msgid ""
"> mkdir $name\n"
"> ls\n"
"Mister Noodle"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:224
msgid ""
"In bash, this would have created two directories \"Mister\" and \"Noodle\". "
"In fish, it created only one: the variable had the value \"Mister Noodle\", "
"so that is the argument that was passed to ``mkdir``, spaces and all."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:226
msgid "You can erase (or \"delete\") a variable with ``-e`` or ``--erase``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:230
msgid ""
"> set -e MyVariable\n"
"> env | grep MyVariable\n"
"(no output)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:234
msgid "For more, see :ref:`Variable expansion <expand-variable>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:239
msgid "Exports (Shell Variables)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:241
msgid ""
"Sometimes you need to have a variable available to an external command, "
"often as a setting. For example many programs like ``git`` or ``man`` read "
"the ``$PAGER`` variable to figure out your preferred pager (the program that "
"lets you scroll text). Other variables used like this include ``$BROWSER``, "
"``$LANG`` (to configure your language) and ``$PATH``. You'll note these are "
"written in ALLCAPS, but that's just a convention."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:243
msgid ""
"To give a variable to an external command, it needs to be \"exported\". This "
"is done with a flag to ``set``, either ``--export`` or just ``-x``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:247
msgid ""
"> set -x MyVariable SomeValue\n"
"> env | grep MyVariable\n"
"MyVariable=SomeValue"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:251
msgid "It can also be unexported with ``--unexport`` or ``-u``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:253
msgid ""
"This works the other way around as well! If fish is started by something "
"else, it inherits that parents exported variables. So if your terminal "
"emulator starts fish, and it exports ``$LANG`` set to ``en_US.UTF-8``, fish "
"will receive that setting. And whatever started your terminal emulator also "
"gave *it* some variables that it will then pass on unless it specifically "
"decides not to. This is how fish usually receives the values for things like "
"``$LANG``, ``$PATH`` and ``$TERM``, without you having to specify them again."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:255
msgid ""
"Exported variables can be local or global or universal - \"exported\" is not "
"a :ref:`scope <variables-scope>`! Usually you'd make them global via ``set -"
"gx MyVariable SomeValue``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:257
msgid "For more, see :ref:`Exporting variables <variables-export>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:262
msgid "Lists"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:264
msgid ""
"The ``set`` command above used quotes to ensure that ``Mister Noodle`` was "
"one argument. If it had been two arguments, then ``name`` would have been a "
"list of length 2.  In fact, all variables in fish are really lists, that can "
"contain any number of values, or none at all."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:266
msgid ""
"Some variables, like ``$PWD``, only have one value. By convention, we talk "
"about that variable's value, but we really mean its first (and only) value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:268
msgid ""
"Other variables, like ``$PATH``, really do have multiple values. During "
"variable expansion, the variable expands to become multiple arguments::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:270
msgid ""
"> echo $PATH\n"
"/usr/bin /bin /usr/sbin /sbin /usr/local/bin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:273
msgid ""
"Variables whose name ends in \"PATH\" are automatically split on colons to "
"become lists. They are joined using colons when exported to subcommands. "
"This is for compatibility with other tools, which expect $PATH to use "
"colons. You can also explicitly add this quirk to a variable with ``set --"
"path``, or remove it with ``set --unpath``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:275
msgid ""
"Lists cannot contain other lists: there is no recursion.  A variable is a "
"list of strings, full stop."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:277
msgid "Get the length of a list with ``count``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:279
msgid ""
"> count $PATH\n"
"5"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:282
msgid ""
"You can append (or prepend) to a list by setting the list to itself, with "
"some additional arguments. Here we append /usr/local/bin to $PATH::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:284
msgid "> set PATH $PATH /usr/local/bin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:286
msgid ""
"You can access individual elements with square brackets. Indexing starts at "
"1 from the beginning, and -1 from the end::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:288
msgid ""
"> echo $PATH\n"
"/usr/bin /bin /usr/sbin /sbin /usr/local/bin\n"
"> echo $PATH[1]\n"
"/usr/bin\n"
"> echo $PATH[-1]\n"
"/usr/local/bin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:295
msgid "You can also access ranges of elements, known as \"slices\":"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:299
msgid ""
"> echo $PATH[1..2]\n"
"/usr/bin /bin\n"
"> echo $PATH[-1..2]\n"
"/usr/local/bin /sbin /usr/sbin /bin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:304
msgid "You can iterate over a list (or a slice) with a for loop::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:306
msgid ""
"for val in $PATH\n"
"  echo \"entry: $val\"\n"
"end\n"
"# Will print:\n"
"# entry: /usr/bin/\n"
"# entry: /bin\n"
"# entry: /usr/sbin\n"
"# entry: /sbin\n"
"# entry: /usr/local/bin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:316
msgid ""
"One particular bit is that you can use lists like :ref:`Brace expansion "
"<expand-brace>`. If you attach another string to a list, it'll combine every "
"element of the list with the string::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:318
msgid ""
"> set mydirs /usr/bin /bin\n"
"> echo $mydirs/fish # this is just like {/usr/bin,/bin}/fish\n"
"/usr/bin/fish /bin/fish"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:322
msgid "This also means that, if the list is empty, there will be no argument::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:324
msgid ""
"> set empty # no argument\n"
"> echo $empty/this_is_gone # prints an empty line"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:327
msgid ""
"If you quote the list, it will be used as one string and so you'll get one "
"argument even if it is empty."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:329
msgid ""
"For more, see :ref:`Lists <variables-lists>`. For more on combining lists "
"with strings (or even other lists), see :ref:`cartesian products <cartesian-"
"product>` and :ref:`Variable expansion <expand-variable>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:333
msgid "Wildcards"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:335
msgid "Fish supports the familiar wildcard ``*``. To list all JPEG files::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:337
msgid ""
"> ls *.jpg\n"
"lena.jpg\n"
"meena.jpg\n"
"santa maria.jpg"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:343
msgid "You can include multiple wildcards::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:345
msgid ""
"> ls l*.p*\n"
"lena.png\n"
"lesson.pdf"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:350
msgid "The recursive wildcard ``**`` searches directories recursively::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:352
msgid ""
"> ls /var/**.log\n"
"/var/log/system.log\n"
"/var/run/sntp.log"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:357
msgid ""
"If that directory traversal is taking a long time, you can :kbd:`ctrl-c` out "
"of it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:359
msgid "For more, see :ref:`Wildcards <expand-wildcard>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:362
msgid "Pipes and Redirections"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:364
msgid "You can pipe between commands with the usual vertical bar::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:366
msgid ""
"> echo hello world | wc\n"
"      1       2      12"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:369
msgid ""
"stdin and stdout can be redirected via the familiar ``<`` and ``>``. stderr "
"is redirected with a ``2>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:373
msgid "> grep fish < /etc/shells > ~/output.txt 2> ~/errors.txt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:375
msgid "To redirect stdout and stderr into one file, you can use ``&>``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:377
msgid "> make &> make_output.txt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:379
msgid ""
"For more, see :ref:`Input and output redirections <redirects>` and :ref:"
"`Pipes <pipes>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:383
msgid "Command Substitutions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:385
msgid ""
"Command substitutions use the output of one command as an argument to "
"another. Unlike other shells, fish does not use backticks `` for command "
"substitutions. Instead, it uses parentheses with or without a dollar::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:387
msgid ""
"> echo In (pwd), running $(uname)\n"
"In /home/tutorial, running FreeBSD"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:390
msgid "A common idiom is to capture the output of a command in a variable::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:392
msgid ""
"> set os (uname)\n"
"> echo $os\n"
"Linux"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:396
msgid ""
"Command substitutions without a dollar are not expanded within quotes, so "
"the version with a dollar is simpler::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:398
msgid ""
"> touch \"testing_$(date +%s).txt\"\n"
"> ls *.txt\n"
"testing_1360099791.txt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:402
msgid ""
"Unlike other shells, fish does not split command substitutions on any "
"whitespace (like spaces or tabs), only newlines. Usually this is a big help "
"because unix commands operate on a line-by-line basis. Sometimes it can be "
"an issue with commands like ``pkg-config`` that print what is meant to be "
"multiple arguments on a single line. To split it on spaces too, use ``string "
"split``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:406
msgid ""
"> printf '%s\\n' (pkg-config --libs gio-2.0)\n"
"-lgio-2.0 -lgobject-2.0 -lglib-2.0\n"
"> printf '%s\\n' (pkg-config --libs gio-2.0 | string split -n \" \")\n"
"-lgio-2.0\n"
"-lgobject-2.0\n"
"-lglib-2.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:413
msgid ""
"If you need a command substitutions output as one argument, without any "
"splits, use quoted command substitution::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:415
msgid ""
"> echo \"first line\n"
"second line\" > myfile\n"
"> set myfile \"$(cat myfile)\"\n"
"> printf '|%s|' $myfile\n"
"|first line\n"
"second line|"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:422
msgid ""
"For more, see :ref:`Command substitution <expand-command-substitution>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:427
msgid "Separating Commands (Semicolon)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:429
msgid ""
"Like other shells, fish allows multiple commands either on separate lines or "
"the same line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:431
msgid ""
"To write them on the same line, use the semicolon (\";\"). That means the "
"following two examples are equivalent::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:433
msgid ""
"echo fish; echo chips\n"
"\n"
"# or\n"
"echo fish\n"
"echo chips"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:439
msgid ""
"This is useful interactively to enter multiple commands. In a script it's "
"easier to read if the commands are on separate lines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:442
msgid "Exit Status"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:444
msgid ""
"When a command exits, it returns a status code as a non-negative integer "
"(that's a whole number >= 0)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:446
msgid ""
"Unlike other shells, fish stores the exit status of the last command in "
"``$status`` instead of ``$?``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:450
msgid ""
"> false\n"
"> echo $status\n"
"1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:454
msgid ""
"This indicates how the command fared - 0 usually means success, while the "
"others signify kinds of failure. For instance fish's ``set --query`` returns "
"the number of variables it queried that weren't set - ``set --query PATH`` "
"usually returns 0, ``set --query arglbargl boogagoogoo`` usually returns 2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:456
msgid ""
"There is also a ``$pipestatus`` list variable for the exit statuses [#]_ of "
"processes in a pipe."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:458
msgid "For more, see :ref:`The status variable <variables-status>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:460
msgid ""
"or \"stati\" if you prefer, or \"statūs\" if you've time-travelled from "
"ancient Rome or work as a latin teacher"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:465
msgid "Combiners (And, Or, Not)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:467
msgid ""
"fish supports the familiar ``&&`` and ``||`` to combine commands, and ``!`` "
"to negate them::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:469
msgid "> ./configure && make && sudo make install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:471
msgid ""
"Here, ``make`` is only executed if ``./configure`` succeeds (returns 0), and "
"``sudo make install`` is only executed if both ``./configure`` and ``make`` "
"succeed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:473
msgid ""
"fish also supports :doc:`and <cmds/and>`, :doc:`or <cmds/or>`, and :doc:`not "
"<cmds/not>`. The first two are job modifiers and have lower precedence. "
"Example usage::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:475
msgid ""
"> cp file1 file1_bak && cp file2 file2_bak; and echo \"Backup successful\"; "
"or echo \"Backup failed\"\n"
"Backup failed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:479
msgid ""
"As mentioned in :ref:`the section on the semicolon <tut-semicolon>`, this "
"can also be written in multiple lines, like so::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:481
msgid ""
"cp file1 file1_bak && cp file2 file2_bak\n"
"and echo \"Backup successful\"\n"
"or echo \"Backup failed\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:486
msgid "Conditionals (If, Else, Switch)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:488
msgid ""
"Use :doc:`if <cmds/if>` and :doc:`else <cmds/else>` to conditionally execute "
"code, based on the exit status of a command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:492
msgid ""
"if grep fish /etc/shells\n"
"    echo Found fish\n"
"else if grep bash /etc/shells\n"
"    echo Found bash\n"
"else\n"
"    echo Got nothing\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:500
msgid ""
"To compare strings or numbers or check file properties (whether a file "
"exists or is writeable and such), use :doc:`test <cmds/test>`, like"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:504
msgid ""
"if test \"$fish\" = \"flounder\"\n"
"    echo FLOUNDER\n"
"end\n"
"\n"
"# or\n"
"\n"
"if test \"$number\" -gt 5\n"
"    echo $number is greater than five\n"
"else\n"
"    echo $number is five or less\n"
"end\n"
"\n"
"# or\n"
"\n"
"# This test is true if the path /etc/hosts exists\n"
"# - it could be a file or directory or symlink (or possibly something "
"else).\n"
"if test -e /etc/hosts\n"
"    echo We most likely have a hosts file\n"
"else\n"
"    echo We do not have a hosts file\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:526
msgid ""
":ref:`Combiners <tut-combiners>` can also be used to make more complex "
"conditions, like"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:530
msgid ""
"if command -sq fish; and grep fish /etc/shells\n"
"    echo fish is installed and configured\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:534
msgid ""
"For even more complex conditions, use :doc:`begin <cmds/begin>` and :doc:"
"`end <cmds/end>` to group parts of them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:536
msgid "There is also a :doc:`switch <cmds/switch>` command::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:538
msgid ""
"switch (uname)\n"
"case Linux\n"
"    echo Hi Tux!\n"
"case Darwin\n"
"    echo Hi Hexley!\n"
"case FreeBSD NetBSD DragonFly\n"
"    echo Hi Beastie!\n"
"case '*'\n"
"    echo Hi, stranger!\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:549
msgid ""
"As you see, :doc:`case <cmds/case>` does not fall through, and can accept "
"multiple arguments or (quoted) wildcards."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:551
msgid "For more, see :ref:`Conditions <syntax-conditional>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:554
msgid "Functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:556
msgid ""
"A fish function is a list of commands, which may optionally take arguments. "
"Unlike other shells, arguments are not passed in \"numbered variables\" like "
"``$1``, but instead in a single list ``$argv``. To create a function, use "
"the :doc:`function <cmds/function>` builtin::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:558
msgid ""
"function say_hello\n"
"    echo Hello $argv\n"
"end\n"
"say_hello\n"
"# prints: Hello\n"
"say_hello everybody!\n"
"# prints: Hello everybody!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:566
msgid ""
"Unlike other shells, fish does not have aliases or special prompt syntax. "
"Functions take their place. [#]_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:568
msgid ""
"You can list the names of all functions with the :doc:`functions <cmds/"
"functions>` builtin (note the plural!). fish starts out with a number of "
"functions::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:570
msgid ""
"> functions\n"
"N_, abbr, alias, bg, cd, cdh, contains_seq, dirh, dirs, disown, down-or-"
"search, edit_command_buffer, export, fg, fish_add_path, "
"fish_breakpoint_prompt, fish_clipboard_copy, fish_clipboard_paste, "
"fish_config, fish_default_key_bindings, fish_default_mode_prompt, "
"fish_git_prompt, fish_hg_prompt, fish_hybrid_key_bindings, fish_indent, "
"fish_is_root_user, fish_job_summary, fish_key_reader, fish_md5, "
"fish_mode_prompt, fish_npm_helper, fish_opt, fish_print_git_action, "
"fish_print_hg_root, fish_prompt, fish_sigtrap_handler, fish_svn_prompt, "
"fish_title, fish_update_completions, fish_vcs_prompt, fish_vi_cursor, "
"fish_vi_key_bindings, funced, funcsave, grep, help, history, hostname, "
"isatty, kill, la, ll, ls, man, nextd, open, popd, prevd, prompt_hostname, "
"prompt_pwd, psub, pushd, realpath, seq, setenv, suspend, trap, type, umask, "
"up-or-search, vared, wait"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:573
msgid ""
"You can see the source for any function by passing its name to "
"``functions``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:575
msgid ""
"> functions ls\n"
"function ls --description 'List contents of directory'\n"
"    command ls -G $argv\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:580
msgid "For more, see :ref:`Functions <syntax-function>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:582
msgid ""
"There is a function called :doc:`alias <cmds/alias>`, but it's just a "
"shortcut to make functions. fish also provides :ref:`abbreviations "
"<abbreviations>`, through the :doc:`abbr <cmds/abbr>` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:585
msgid "Loops"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:587
msgid "While loops::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:589
msgid ""
"while true\n"
"    echo \"Loop forever\"\n"
"end\n"
"# Prints:\n"
"# Loop forever\n"
"# Loop forever\n"
"# Loop forever\n"
"# yes, this really will loop forever. Unless you abort it with ctrl-c."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:598
msgid ""
"For loops can be used to iterate over a list. For example, a list of files::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:600
msgid ""
"for file in *.txt\n"
"    cp $file $file.bak\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:604
msgid "Iterating over a list of numbers can be done with ``seq``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:606
msgid ""
"for x in (seq 5)\n"
"    touch file_$x.txt\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:610
msgid "For more, see :ref:`Loops and blocks <syntax-loops-and-blocks>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:613
msgid "Prompt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:617
msgid ""
"Unlike other shells, there is no prompt variable like ``PS1``. To display "
"your prompt, fish executes the :doc:`fish_prompt <cmds/fish_prompt>` "
"function and uses its output as the prompt. And if it exists, fish also "
"executes the :doc:`fish_right_prompt <cmds/fish_right_prompt>` function and "
"uses its output as the right prompt."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:619
msgid "You can define your own prompt from the command line:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:624
msgid ""
"> function fish_prompt; echo \"New Prompt % \"; end\n"
"New Prompt % _"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:628
msgid ""
"Then, if you are happy with it, you can save it to disk by typing ``funcsave "
"fish_prompt``. This saves the prompt in ``~/.config/fish/functions/"
"fish_prompt.fish``. (Or, if you want, you can create that file manually from "
"the start.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:630
msgid ""
"Multiple lines are OK. Colors can be set via :doc:`set_color <cmds/"
"set_color>` by passing it named ANSI colors, or hex RGB values::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:632
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    set_color purple\n"
"    date \"+%m/%d/%y\"\n"
"    set_color FF0000\n"
"    echo (pwd) '>' (set_color normal)\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:640
msgid "This prompt would look like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:645
msgid ""
":purple:`02/06/13`\n"
":red:`/home/tutorial >` _"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:649
msgid "See also :doc:`Writing your own prompt <prompt>`."
msgstr "另請參見\\ :doc:`編寫你自己的提示 <prompt>`。"

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:651
msgid ""
"You can choose among sample prompts by running ``fish_config`` for a web UI "
"or ``fish_config prompt`` for a simpler version inside your terminal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:654
msgid "$PATH"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:656
msgid ""
"``$PATH`` is an environment variable containing the directories that fish "
"searches for commands. Unlike other shells, $PATH is a :ref:`list <tut-"
"lists>`, not a colon-delimited string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:658
msgid ""
"Fish takes care to set ``$PATH`` to a default, but typically it is just "
"inherited from fish's parent process and is set to a value that makes sense "
"for the system - see :ref:`Exports <tut-exports>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:660
msgid "To prepend /usr/local/bin and /usr/sbin to ``$PATH``, you can write::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:662
msgid "> set PATH /usr/local/bin /usr/sbin $PATH"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:665
msgid "To remove /usr/local/bin from ``$PATH``, you can write::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:667
msgid "> set PATH (string match -v /usr/local/bin $PATH)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:669
msgid ""
"For compatibility with other shells and external commands, $PATH is a :ref:"
"`path variable<variables-path>`, and so will be joined with colons (not "
"spaces) when you quote it::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:671
msgid ""
"> echo \"$PATH\"\n"
"/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:674
msgid ""
"and it will be exported like that, and when fish starts it splits the $PATH "
"it receives into a list on colon."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:676
msgid ""
"You can do so directly in ``config.fish``, like you might do in other shells "
"with ``.profile``. See :ref:`this example <path_example>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:678
msgid ""
"A faster way is to use the :doc:`fish_add_path <cmds/fish_add_path>` "
"function, which adds given directories to the path if they aren't already "
"included. It does this by modifying the ``$fish_user_paths`` :ref:`universal "
"variable <tut-universal>`, which is automatically prepended to ``$PATH``. "
"For example, to permanently add ``/usr/local/bin`` to your ``$PATH``, you "
"could write::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:680
msgid "> fish_add_path /usr/local/bin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:683
msgid ""
"The advantage is that you don't have to go mucking around in files: just run "
"this once at the command line, and it will affect the current session and "
"all future instances too. You can also add this line to :ref:`config.fish "
"<tut-config>`, as it only adds the component if necessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:685
msgid ""
"Or you can modify $fish_user_paths yourself, but you should be careful *not* "
"to append to it unconditionally in config.fish, or it will grow longer and "
"longer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:690
msgid "Startup (Where's .bashrc?)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:692
msgid ""
"Fish starts by executing commands in ``~/.config/fish/config.fish``. You can "
"create it if it does not exist."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:694
msgid ""
"It is possible to directly create functions and variables in ``config.fish`` "
"file, using the commands shown above. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:700
msgid ""
"> cat ~/.config/fish/config.fish\n"
"\n"
"set -x PATH $PATH /sbin/\n"
"\n"
"function ll\n"
"    ls -lh $argv\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:709
msgid ""
"However, it is more common and efficient to use  autoloading functions and "
"universal variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:711
msgid ""
"If you want to organize your configuration, fish also reads commands in ."
"fish files in ``~/.config/fish/conf.d/``. See :ref:`Configuration Files "
"<configuration>` for the details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:714
msgid "Autoloading Functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:716
msgid ""
"When fish encounters a command, it attempts to autoload a function for that "
"command, by looking for a file with the name of that command in ``~/.config/"
"fish/functions/``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:718
msgid ""
"For example, if you wanted to have a function ``ll``, you would add a text "
"file ``ll.fish`` to ``~/.config/fish/functions``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:720
msgid ""
"> cat ~/.config/fish/functions/ll.fish\n"
"function ll\n"
"    ls -lh $argv\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:726
msgid "This is the preferred way to define your prompt as well::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:728
msgid ""
"> cat ~/.config/fish/functions/fish_prompt.fish\n"
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    echo (pwd) \"> \"\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:734
msgid ""
"See the documentation for :doc:`funced <cmds/funced>` and :doc:`funcsave "
"<cmds/funcsave>` for ways to create these files automatically, and :ref:"
"`$fish_function_path <syntax-function-autoloading>` to control their "
"location."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:739
msgid "Universal Variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:741
msgid ""
"A universal variable is a variable whose value is shared across all "
"instances of fish, now and in the future – even after a reboot. You can make "
"a variable universal with ``set -U``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:743
msgid "> set -U EDITOR vim"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:746
msgid "Now in another shell::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:748
msgid ""
"> echo $EDITOR\n"
"vim"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:751
msgid ""
"You only need to set universal variables once interactively. There is no "
"need to add them to your :ref:`config files <configuration>`. For more "
"details, see :ref:`Universal Variables <variables-universal>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:754
msgid "Ready for more?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorial.rst:756
msgid ""
"If you want to learn more about fish, there is :ref:`lots of detailed "
"documentation <intro>`, the `official gitter channel <https://gitter.im/fish-"
"shell/fish-shell>`__, an `official mailing list <https://lists.sourceforge."
"net/lists/listinfo/fish-users>`__, and the `github page <https://github.com/"
"fish-shell/fish-shell/>`__."
msgstr ""
